function isPrime(num) {
  for (let i = 2; i < num; i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return num > 1;
}

var numbers = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
var isPrimeNum = isPrime(numbers.length);
if (isPrimeNum) {
  console.log(numbers[0] + " is a prime number.");
} else {
  console.log(numbers[0] + " is not a prime number.");
}
```

In this function, we iterate from 2 to the given number and check if any number divides it equally. If we find a number that divides the given number, it means the number is not prime. If we reached the end of the range without finding a number that divides it, it means the number is prime. We return true if we find a prime number, and false otherwise. In the given array [2, 3, 4, 5, 6], the function prints "2 is a prime number." because it is a valid prime number.

